Ring designed for the FIERCE Competition. FIERCE is a drone competition in the Fox Valley area in Wisconsin, USA.

There are three different ring sizes and two (three for 1" ring) different thicknesses. The larger rings are designed for larger drones that can carry heaver payloads, and the smaller ones are for the smaller drones. The thickness goes as follows-
Thick=0.500" thick Thin=0.250" Tiny=0.125
Only two different rings have been 'standardized'. The 5" rings thin variation should weigh 5.00 grams, while the thick version should weigh around 10 grams.

Besides my casting box (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1240561) I used a casting ring for some models.

Now, as I had to change the FreeCAD file another time to print the ring at a different size, I decided to make an scad thing and to share it as a customizer.

Open the customizer (apps). Just change the hight and the diameter to your needs. Eventually you have to change the „tolerance“ if the two halves are too loose or too tight. There is no need to change the „wandstaerke“, which means thickness of the walls.

Print it and stick the two halves together. Mark them with a felt marker, so you can always put them together in the same position. Now you are good to go.

In short, what it´s good for:
Put you model on a table, lay the first ring around it, fill it with molding sand, compress the sand, take up the form, stick the other half on and fill again with sand. Now take the halfes apart, remove the model, make a pour hole, maby annother smaler one for the air to come out. Stick the two halfs togeter again fix them with a clamp and pour in the hot metal :)

I have now printed 2 complete sets of Mendel.  I switched to these files after the 1st print.  This breaks a Mendel down into 24 prints, averaging 2-3 hours a print.  It also uses the smaller RP parts to hold down the raft for the larger prints.  It works pretty good (but not as good as a heated plate).  The good thing is that this design works just as good with no raft on a hot plate.
To use just export each "plate" as a separate stl, skeinforge and print.  I have them separated on my computer but that's a lot of files to upload.
Also I included the non joined plates, so if you can find a way to turn it into a 23 or 22 plate print please improve on my work.
This is the easiest way to print Mendel I have found, and the beautiful part is if you are using something with a larger build plate than a Makerbot, just join four of these and you can print Mendel in 6 prints!
Much Props to Ryan P, and Cyrozap for fixing my broken files.  I don't know how those got messed up, but they fixed it, and dealt with my VERY slow responce.
Honestly I was print 1 of these and not noticing it was build in the air, the other I fixed in my person sel, and never uploaded the fix.  Their fixes where better than mine.
So now ALL these should work 100%.  If they don't email me the fix and flame me in the comments!
Have fun!

title: Disc brake set 1 for the Traxxas  1/16 E Revo

description.text:
I design this disc brake set for my traxxas 1/16 e-revo this is a
cosmetic upgrade as you see here in the photos. If you wish to
download this file. The requirements for these 3-D printed disc brakes
you must have the RPM axle carriers already installed onto your
traxxas 1/16 e revo like you see here in the photos. The photos
will give you an idea on how to prepare them and install them but
I will explain to you step-by-step how to prepare them and to install
them.

1 depending upon your 3-D printer you would need to do some sanding
with a dremel or similar power tool to smooth out all of the rough edges.

2 remove the hex nut on the axle carrier and do a test fit to make sure that
everything fits as seen in one of the photos.

3 once the pieces have been sanded out and test fitted then assemble the pads
onto the discs themselves as seen here in one of the photos.

4 then use a little amount of superglue to secure the pads and to the
discs themselves as seen here in one of the photos and let the glue dry.

5 after that then use then hot glue gun then applied a small amount of glue
on the discs themselves not too much because you may have to remove the disc brakes
for maintenance or repairs later. After applying hot glue onto the disk brakes
or axle carriers themselves and quickly install the disgraced themselves and to
the axle carrier before the glue dries.

6 after that the glue is dry test everything out to make sure that the disk brakes
themselves are solid on the axle carrier themselves.

7 after that put the hex nuts themselves back onto the axle carriers then
put the wheels back on and test out the RC vehicle to make sure that they are no
issues in regards to the disk brakes themselves and everything should work out.

title: Vast Board Game Print & Play Components
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Here are the component files I designed for the board game Vast: The Crystal Caverns. You'll find pawns for all of the characters (and a sticker sheet to print out), treasure chests, thief vaults, and basically all of the disks, cubes, and tokens you'll need if you decide to make your own bits for the game. Files for all of the tiles, cards, boards, etc of the game are available online - visit the publisher's website (ledergames.com) to learn all about it. Note that I believe the link to the pnp files are near the bottom of the game's kickstarter page, so you'll have to navigate a bit. But start at Leder Games, that way you can learn all about Vast first. Or visit boardgamegeek.com and search for Vast, you'll find lots of info there too.

It's a great game, a highly asymmetric dungeon battle. It is a very big job to build the entire thing from scratch, it's definitely not a beginner gaming project. So it may be cheaper and easier to just buy the game from Leder Games. :)

That said, here's a rundown of what you'll need to print if you go the pnp route:

Red
One Dragon Asleep Pawn (Black or Red)
One Dragon Awake Pawn (Black or Red)
Four 25mm Disks (for Goblins)
Three Red 10mm Cubes (2 for Hero, 1 for Dragon)

Dark Brown
Two 21mm Disks (Dragon Shriek & Firewall Tokens)
Fourteen 10mm Cubes (for Dragon)

Dark Purple
Thirty-Six 25mm Squares (for Cave Omens)
Thirteen 21mm Disks (for Cave Events & Rockfall Tokens)

Light Purple (or whatever color you prefer)
Three 21mm Disk (for Dragon Gem Tokens)
Nine Giant Crystals

Green
One Green 10mm Cube (for Dragon)
Three 21mm Disks (for Goblins)
Twelve 25mm Disks (for Goblins)
Three Goblin Tribe Pawns

Yellow or Tan
One Knight Pawn
Seven 10mm Cubes (for Knight)
Three 21mm Disks (for Knight Bomb Tokens)

Gold
Six Vault Gold ‘Slugs’ (see assembly note)
Six Closed Treasure Chests
Six Open Treasure Chests (actually the ratio of open/closed can be whatever you want)

Light Grey
Six Vault Stonework (see assembly note)

Dark Grey
One Thief Pawn
Four 21mm Disks (for Thief)
Five 10mm Cubes (for Thief)

I should also note that there is one component that I did not design. The Giant Crystals listed here were created by Tothe, I simply scaled them to fit on the Vast tiles. They're fantastic and really fit the game well.

When printing the vaults for the Thief there is some assembly required. First print all of your Gold (the Vault Gold file). Then start printing your Vault Stonework pieces, but set your printer to pause at 5mm. When it pauses insert a gold piece into each in-progress stonework. Start the print back up and you'll have a slug of little gold coins printed inside the vault. Be careful when you do this - if you don't get the gold slug seated all the way into the stonework cavity it'll interfere with the head of your printer! I take no responsibility for any damage or issues you have in doing this - be careful. The worst thing that happened to me was my stepper motor whined for a couple of seconds and I had a botched print.

Enjoy!

title: MK6 Stepstruder cooling mod for PLA

description.text:
I was having problems printing PLA with my TOM, after a period of time the heat would conduct through the stainless steel pipe and melt the PLA near the drive gear (causing it to bind up and stop extruding).
I tried to solve the problem by adding some heat sinks made from coins with an 8mm hole in the centre but on long prints (2+ hours) the PLA was still melting. 
I had a 40mm fan lying around so I redesigned the back part of the acrylic Stepstruder support to accomodate a fan that blows air directly on to the SS pipe. I stuck a thermometer on the top of the pipe and it's now at a temperature of 26C so no way close to melting the PLA.

I've included all of the acrylic parts in the file despite only redesigning one piece, this is because makerbot suggest using superglue to join the bottom plates, I went a bit crazy with the glue and most of my parts were stuck together. It was easier to make the whole thing again than unstick the parts.
Laser cut from 5mm acrylic in whatever colour you want then counter sink the holes. Use 2 M3 x 30 CSK screws and 2 M3 nuts to attach the fan.
I hard wired the fan to the 12v supply, but alternatively it could be wired to the FAN output of the EC board.

title: Mounting Plate Frame for 8x8 LED Module Array Matrix
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This design provides for mounting multiple 8x8 LED array modules. The design is configurable for the number of LED arrays in the horizontal and vertical directions, so it can be tailored for a range of applications. The frame is no larger than the LED arrays mounted to it; this allows zip ties or other mechanical fasteners to be used to join multiple frames for a display larger than can be printed at one time.

The driver chips on the circuit boards for the LED arrays typically use a Maxim MAX7219 or MAX7221, or AMS AS1106 or AS1107. Boards with driver chips in a SOIC package can be sized to match the 8x8 LED matrices. Boards with driver chips in a DIP package are larger, with the DIP driver chip located outside the LED matrix.

The original design was developed for use with "LED Matrix Link v2.0" available at https://oshpark.com/shared_projects/J1PUJCGP. The v2.0 board is an adaptation of the LED Matrix Link board available from https://friedcircuits.us/. I liked the friedcircuits approach since it puts the SOIC driver chip on the side of the board away from the LED module, improving its ability to dissipate any generated heat. The friedcircuits approach also allows right-angle headers to be used to interconnect LED modules. My v2.0 revision was driven by a preference for through-hole capacitors and resistor, and a desire to beef up trace widths - especially for the trace handling 5V power daisy chained for multiple modules. I also trimmed the board dimensions a bit, adjusted placements of the four mounting holes to provide more room for screw heads, and added silkscreen for a serial number label.

The rev A version of the openSCAD script adds flexibility in handling multiple types of module boards. In addition to the original v2.0 Matrix Link, sample dimension data is provided in the openSCAD file for the Friedcircuits Matrix Link v1.2, generic boards marked as FC-16 type, and the larger generic boards using DIP-style MAX7219 driver chips located outside the LED array. Selection of the desired board type is handled through commenting/uncommenting the appropriate dimension data.

Sample STL files are provided for 3-by-2 configurations of the frame for the Matrix Link v2.0, Friedcircuits Matrix Link v1.2, and FC-16 type driver boards. The sample STL file for the DIP-style MAX7219 is provided in a 3-by-1 configuration. All have mounting holes sizes for threading M2.5 hardware.

The openSCAD file has been extensively commented for those wishing to tailor the design.

Use of mounting hardware to attach the boards to the printed frame means that the LED arrays cannot be directly soldered to the boards. Single Inline Package (SIP) sockets should be soldered to the boards, and the LED arrays inserted into the SIP sockets.

description.text:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B3PxFX8ozxI

This is a dust shoe attachment for the Inventables X-Carve with the DeWalt DWP611 Router option. Adding a dust shoe is an easy and inexpensive way to upgrade your X-Carve. The dust shoe connects to a vacuum that extracts the chips created while cutting. The chips no longer get caught up in the cutting tool during each pass and do not get deposited on the rails for cleaner, more accurate cuts.

The dust shoe itself is 3D printed and the file is below for your convenience. The dust shoe easily attaches to the side of the router mount on the X-Carve using 1 to 2 M3 X 16mm socket head screws. A separate vacuum hose snugly fits into the dust shoe. This makes it easy for removal for post carving cleanup if needed. There is also a 3D printed adapter piece for the two different brand hoses I used. You may or may not need this for your build.

Check out my blog post for more information and video. https://blog.ohmnilabs.com/low-cost-dust-shoe-for-the-x-carve-cnc-router

title: RPMBlade Fidget Toy (12mm Bearing Weights, For Large Hands)

description.text:
A Friend of mine recently wanted me to 3D print him a fidget toy. This sounded simple enough, until he gave me the bearings that he wanted to use for weights. These were no ordinary 608 bearings, but 60012 12mm bearings. This caused me to draw up my own model in Autodesk 123D design. THIS IS FOR LARGER HANDS, AND FOR PEOPLE WHO WANT HEAVIER WEIGHTS.

I believe in posting very specific instructions on Thingiverse, rather than letting the user fend for themselves and figure out which files are the right ones to print, so, as one could infer, I will always write instructions for all of my published things.

Please feel free to ask questions, as I will gladly answer! Post any pictures of you making it as well!

Printer:

M3D Micro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

30% nozzle diameter

Infill:

30%

Notes:

I would recommend printing the actual frame of the spinner with an impact-resistant material, such as ABS (I used black, no-name ABS at 260 degrees Celsius). PLA is somewhat brittle, and may cause the model to shatter if dropped. If you do not have a heated bed for ABS, simply cover the print bed with a PVA based glue stick (I like to use the purple Elmer's brand glue sticks). The Finger Rests are made to be printed with flexible filament for nice and comfortable grips that aren't as taxing on the fingers. I used Sainsmart Red TPU at 220 degrees Celsius.

Very little, if any ,cleanup is required. Depending on the printer, stringing may occur. Bearings and finger rests are to be glued in place using fast-drying "Krazy-glue" or something similar. All holes were made to loosely fit the bearings without large amounts of pressure.
